            <section>
                <div class="container">
                    <div class=" position-relative w-100">
                        <div class="accordion">
                            <div style="border-bottom: 3px solid #2f94e1;">
                                <h2 class="mb-0 text-color3">Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)</h2>
                            </div>

                            <div class="accordion__item">
                                <button class="accordion__btn">
                                    <span class="accordion__caption"><i class="far fa-lightbulb"></i>Can degenerative disc disease be cured completely?</span>
                                    <span class="accordion__icon"><i class="fa fa-plus"></i></span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion__content">
                                    <p>In strict medical terms, the wear-and-tear changes in a degenerated disc are not literally reversed &mdash; you cannot make an old disc young again. But this is not the whole story. The vast majority of people become genuinely pain-free and fully active by treating the problem consistently: correct diagnosis, targeted physiotherapy, core strengthening, posture and weight control, and staying active. When we say patients are &lsquo;cured&rsquo;, we mean they live a full, pain-controlled life without the condition limiting them.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="accordion__item">
                                <button class="accordion__btn">
                                    <span class="accordion__caption"><i class="far fa-lightbulb"></i>Is degenerative disc disease a serious or disabling condition?</span>
                                    <span class="accordion__icon"><i class="fa fa-plus"></i></span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion__content">
                                    <p>For most people it is not disabling. Degenerative disc disease is a very common part of ageing, and disc changes are seen on the scans of many people who have no pain at all. It becomes a problem only when it causes persistent pain or presses on a nerve. With the right plan the outlook is very good, and only a small minority ever need surgery.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="accordion__item">
                                <button class="accordion__btn">
                                    <span class="accordion__caption"><i class="far fa-lightbulb"></i>How long does it take to become pain-free from degenerative disc disease?</span>
                                    <span class="accordion__icon"><i class="fa fa-plus"></i></span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion__content">
                                    <p>Most flare-ups settle within a few weeks, but building lasting relief through strengthening and posture change usually takes about 6 to 12 weeks of consistent effort, and sometimes a few months. Recovery is rarely a straight line &mdash; there are good days and bad days. The people who do best are those who stay patient and stick with their exercises even after the sharp pain has gone.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="accordion__item">
                                <button class="accordion__btn">
                                    <span class="accordion__caption"><i class="far fa-lightbulb"></i>Can I exercise with degenerative disc disease, or will it make it worse?</span>
                                    <span class="accordion__icon"><i class="fa fa-plus"></i></span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion__content">
                                    <p>Correctly guided exercise is one of the most powerful treatments for degenerative disc disease, not a danger. Strengthening the core and back muscles gives the spine a supportive &lsquo;natural belt&rsquo; that offloads the worn disc. What harms is the wrong movement &mdash; heavy, jerky lifting or high-impact activity during a severe flare. Start under a physiotherapist's guidance, progress gradually, and stay within a sensible pain limit.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="accordion__item">
                                <button class="accordion__btn">
                                    <span class="accordion__caption"><i class="far fa-lightbulb"></i>Does degenerative disc disease always need surgery?</span>
                                    <span class="accordion__icon"><i class="fa fa-plus"></i></span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion__content">
                                    <p>No. The great majority of cases improve with non-surgical care &mdash; physiotherapy, exercise, posture correction, weight management and sensible pain relief. Surgery is considered only in select situations, such as progressive weakness, signs of serious nerve or spinal cord compression, or severe pain that does not settle despite a proper course of conservative treatment. That decision is always made by an experienced specialist based on your scans and symptoms.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="accordion__item">
                                <button class="accordion__btn">
                                    <span class="accordion__caption"><i class="far fa-lightbulb"></i>What is the best sleeping position for degenerative disc disease?</span>
                                    <span class="accordion__icon"><i class="fa fa-plus"></i></span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion__content">
                                    <p>The best position is the one that keeps your spine in its natural alignment. For back pain, lying on your back with a pillow under the knees, or on your side with a pillow between the knees, usually works well. Use a mattress that is firm but not rock-hard, and avoid sleeping on your stomach, which strains the neck and lower back. Good sleep posture allows the discs to rest and recover overnight.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="accordion__item">
                                <button class="accordion__btn">
                                    <span class="accordion__caption"><i class="far fa-lightbulb"></i>Can walking help degenerative disc disease?</span>
                                    <span class="accordion__icon"><i class="fa fa-plus"></i></span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion__content">
                                    <p>Yes &mdash; walking is one of the simplest and most effective things you can do. It keeps the spine mobile, nourishes the discs, strengthens supporting muscles and helps with weight control, all without jarring the joints. A brisk 30-minute walk on most days is an excellent goal. If walking triggers leg pain or numbness, mention it to your doctor, as it can be a useful clue about which nerve is involved.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div class="accordion__item">
                                <button class="accordion__btn">
                                    <span class="accordion__caption"><i class="far fa-lightbulb"></i>Will my degenerative disc disease get worse as I age?</span>
                                    <span class="accordion__icon"><i class="fa fa-plus"></i></span>
                                </button>
                                <div class="accordion__content">
                                    <p>Disc changes do tend to progress slowly with age, but pain and disability do not automatically follow. Many people find their symptoms actually settle over the years as the affected segment stiffens and stabilises. Staying at a healthy weight, keeping the core strong, not smoking and staying active are the best ways to keep the condition quiet and protect your spine for the long term.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

